<article>
    <h1>Comet&#x2019;s 2020 Earth odyssey</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200716/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-16"><time>2020-07-16</time></a>
        - <span>BIG PICTURE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A comet has been cap­tured on cam­era streak­ing across the sky over Stone­henge in Eng­land.</p>
    <p>Comet Ne­o­wise has been spot­ted by stargaz­ers across the United King­dom and around the world as it heads past Earth.</p>
    <p>It was dis­cov­ered in late March and be­came one of the few comets in the 21st cen­tury that could be seen with the naked eye as it ap­proached the Sun.</p>
    <p>The comet will be clos­est to Earth next Thurs­day but will still be about 103 mil­lion km away.</p>
    <p>The in­ter­plan­e­tary ice­berg will be vis­i­ble through­out this month in the North­ern Hemi­sphere, mov­ing in a west­erly di­rec­tion across the sky.</p>
    <p>From the mid­dle of the month, it will be vis­i­ble low in the sky to­wards the north, through­out the night. It will then head out of sight as it trav­els back to the outer so­lar sys­tem.</p>

